  "text": "The Apache Kafka consumer group coordinator's state machine is implemented across multiple Java source files in the group-coordinator module. The implementation includes two distinct patterns: the classic group coordination protocol and the modern (KIP-848) group coordination protocol.\n\n## Classic Group State Machine\n\nThe classic protocol is defined in the following files:\n\n1. **ClassicGroupState.java** - Defines an enum with five states:\n   - EMPTY: Group has no members, waiting for joins\n   - PREPARING_REBALANCE: Group is initiating a rebalance, collecting join requests\n   - COMPLETING_REBALANCE: Group awaits state assignment from leader\n   - STABLE: Group is stable with members assigned\n   - DEAD: Group is being deleted\n\n   The state enum includes validPreviousStates() method defining valid transitions:\n   - EMPTY -> PREPARING_REBALANCE\n   - PREPARING_REBALANCE -> EMPTY or COMPLETING_REBALANCE\n   - COMPLETING_REBALANCE -> STABLE\n   - STABLE -> PREPARING_REBALANCE\n\n2. **ClassicGroup.java** - Implements the group state machine with:\n   - transitionTo(ClassicGroupState) method for state transitions\n   - assertValidTransition() to enforce valid state changes\n   - canRebalance() to check if group can enter rebalance\n\n3. **ClassicGroupMember.java** - Represents individual members in classic groups\n\n## Modern Consumer Group State Machine\n\nThe modern protocol (introduced in KIP-848) is implemented in:\n\n1. **ConsumerGroup.java** - Defines ConsumerGroupState enum with five states:\n   - EMPTY: No members in group\n   - ASSIGNING: Group is computing target assignments\n   - RECONCILING: Members are reconciling to target assignments\n   - STABLE: All members reconciled\n   - DEAD: Group being deleted\n\n   State transitions are computed in maybeUpdateGroupState() method based on:\n   - Members list emptiness\n   - Comparison of groupEpoch vs targetAssignmentEpoch\n   - Whether members are reconciled to target assignment\n\n2. **CurrentAssignmentBuilder.java** - Encapsulates the reconciliation state machine that determines member states during ASSIGNING and RECONCILING phases\n\n3. **MemberState.java** (modern) - Defines individual member states:\n   - STABLE: Member fully reconciled\n   - UNREVOKED_PARTITIONS: Member must revoke partitions\n   - UNRELEASED_PARTITIONS: Member waiting for partitions from other owners\n   - UNKNOWN: Unknown state\n\n4. **ConsumerGroupMember.java** - Individual member implementation\n\n## Share and Streams Group State Machines\n\nSimilar state machines exist for:\n- **ShareGroup.java** with states: EMPTY, STABLE, DEAD, UNKNOWN\n- **StreamsGroup.java** with member-based reconciliation\n\n## Request Handling and Transitions\n\nThe primary entry points for state transitions are:\n\n1. **GroupMetadataManager.java** - Central coordinator containing:\n   - classicGroupJoin() - Handles JoinGroup requests\n   - classicGroupSync() - Handles SyncGroup requests\n   - consumerGroupHeartbeat() - Handles heartbeat for modern groups\n   - Supporting methods: classicGroupJoinToClassicGroup(), classicGroupJoinNewMember(), classicGroupJoinExistingMember(), classicGroupSyncToClassicGroup()\n\n2. **GroupCoordinatorShard.java** - Delegates to GroupMetadataManager:\n   - classicGroupJoin() - Routes join requests\n   - classicGroupSync() - Routes sync requests\n\n3. **GroupCoordinatorService.java** - API layer:\n   - joinGroup() - Exposes JoinGroup API\n   - syncGroup() - Exposes SyncGroup API\n\n## State Transition Flow\n\nFor classic groups, the flow is:\n1. Member sends JoinGroup -> moves to PREPARING_REBALANCE\n2. After timeout or all members joined -> moves to COMPLETING_REBALANCE\n3. Leader sends SyncGroup with assignments -> moves to STABLE\n4. Any member failure or new join -> moves back to PREPARING_REBALANCE\n\nFor modern consumer groups:\n1. First member join -> ASSIGNING\n2. Compute target assignments -> stays ASSIGNING until assignments available\n3. Members reconcile -> RECONCILING\n4. All members reconciled -> STABLE\n\nThe state machine is driven by records persisted in __consumer_offsets topics, making it durable and recoverable."
